	<td>User requirements: They are written in natural language so that both customers can verify their requirements have been correctly identified</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td>verifyText</td>
	<td>//div[@id='contents']/ul[3]/li</td>
	<td>Functional requirements (FRs): These describe the functionality of a system -- how a system should react to a particular set of inputs and what should be the corresponding output.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td>verifyText</td>
	<td>//div[@id='contents']/ul[5]/li</td>
	<td>Identify the high level functional requirements simply from the conceptual understanding of the problem. For example, a Library Management System, apart from anything else, should be able to issue and return books.</td>
